The Federal Capital Territory Administration (FCTA), says the health needs of the vulnerable, especially the Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs) was a major concern of the administration during the Covid-19 pandemic. Director-General, FCT Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), Alhaji Abbas Idriss stated this when a team of Medical Aid Workers under the auspices of Binta Free Medical Outreach Africa, an NGO, visited in Abuja on Friday. Idriss, who is also the Chairman, FCT Palliative Committee On Covid-19, said FEMA would collaborate with NGOs to ensure that IDPs in FCTA benefit from their wealth of knowledge. He emphasised that the administration was concern about the health of vulnerable people and IDPs. The director-general said the Medical expertise of Binta Free Medical Outreach Africa would be of great benefit in taking care of the health needs of the IDPs because “health is wealth.” Earlier, President and Chief Executive Officer of the NGO, Binta Jalingo, said that they were in FEMA to seek support in reaching out to the IDPs. Jalingo explained that the NGO was a composition of medical professionals who are committed in improving the health of common man who needs to access healthcare facilities not only in the whole of Africa. She said her NGO decided to support the efforts of the Nigerian government during the COVID-19 pandemic by offering free medical outreach to the vulnerable groups. She also expressed determination of the NGO to educate citizens on how to utilise preventive safety equipment. According to Jalingo, most of the IDPs do know how to use these products. ” You cannot donate Sanitisers, gloves, Soap and face masks without educating them on the proper way to make use of them,” she said. Jalingo disclosed that the NGO would visit IDP Camps in Borno, Yobe, Adamawa, Benue, Taraba and Zamfara States. She said that the NGO had earlier took it’s free Medical Outreach to Libya, Niger Republic, Cameroon amongst other African Countries.(NAN)